      <h2>The Problem: Narrative Theory Without Infrastructure</h2>
<SketchContainer sketchId="lenses" height="var(--space-4xl)" mobileHeight="var(--space-3xl)" ariaLabel="Overlapping narrative lens refraction" />

<ShibuiContent id="narratological-lenses.the-problem-narrative-theory-without-infrastructure.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I noticed that narrative analysis has a century of precise structural frameworks -- Propp's plot functions, Genette's discourse taxonomy -- but none of them are executable. They exist only as paper artifacts. I built this project to turn those frameworks into typed Python algorithms with confidence scores and testable assertions.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
      <p>
        Narrative analysis has operated for a century on frameworks that are structurally precise but computationally inert. Vladimir Propp demonstrated in 1928 that Russian wondertales could be decomposed into thirty-one sequential functions — a formal grammar of plot — yet his <ShibuiTerm term="Propp's morphology" definition="Vladimir Propp's 1928 discovery that all Russian fairy tales share the same thirty-one sequential plot functions, forming a universal grammar of narrative structure" /> remained a paper artifact, executed only by human readers marking up texts by hand.<Cite id={1} author="Propp, Vladimir" title="Morphology of the Folktale" source="University of Texas Press" year={1928} /> <ShibuiTerm term="Genette's framework" definition="Gerard Genette's systematic taxonomy for analyzing narrative discourse across five dimensions: order, duration, frequency, mood, and voice" /> — distinguishing order, duration, frequency, mood, and voice — provided an analytical apparatus of extraordinary precision, yet it too remained confined to close reading, applicable only at the pace of a single scholar working through a single text.<Cite id={2} author="Genette, Gerard" title="Narrative Discourse: An Essay in Method" source="Cornell University Press" year={1972} /> This project asks what happens when these frameworks stop being interpretive vocabularies and become executable algorithms: typed Python models with diagnostic outputs, confidence scores, and testable assertions. The goal is not to automate literary criticism but to give narrative theory the same computational infrastructure that other formal disciplines — linguistics, logic, mathematics — have long taken for granted.
      </p>
	</span>
</ShibuiContent>
