      <h2>The Script Doctor</h2>
      <p>
        The Script Doctor is a collaborative AI analysis mode that simulates a writers' room consultation between master creators. Users select a pairing — Tarkovsky and Bergman debating pacing, Larry David and Aristotle clashing over comedic structure, Phoebe Waller-Bridge prescribing fixes for a faltering second act — and the system generates a structured diagnostic conversation formatted as a philosophical debate between the selected frameworks. The Script Doctor draws on the compendium's formalized frameworks to ground each creator's perspective in specific analytical primitives: Tarkovsky's feedback will reference time-pressure metrics, Bergman's will reference interiority scores, and the South Park framework will evaluate causal binding ratios. This is not arbitrary persona simulation but framework-grounded analysis delivered through an accessible conversational interface.<Cite id={7} author="Moretti, Franco" title="Distant Reading" source="Verso Books" year={2013} /> Moretti's argument that computational methods should complement rather than replace close reading applies precisely: the Script Doctor uses quantitative diagnostics to identify structural issues, then presents them through the interpretive vocabulary of specific creative traditions.
      </p>

      <h2>Diagnostic Output: Beyond Classification</h2>
<ShibuiContent id="narratological-lenses.diagnostic-output-beyond-classification.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I designed the output as a full diagnostic, not a label. When the engine runs a Proppian analysis, it reports which functions were found, at what confidence, with what evidence, and which expected functions are missing. This structured format lets different analyses be cross-referenced and aggregated across large corpora.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
      <p>
        The system's output is not a label but a diagnostic — a structured report that tells the analyst not just <em>what</em> was detected but <em>how confident</em> the detection is, <em>what evidence</em> supports it, and <em>what structural relations</em> connect it to other detections. When the engine runs a Proppian analysis, it does not simply say "this is a hero's journey." It reports precisely which morphological functions were detected, at what confidence level, with what ordering violations (if any), and which functions are expected but absent.<Cite id={7} author="Moretti, Franco" title="Distant Reading" source="Verso Books" year={2013} /> Moretti's argument for "<ShibuiTerm term="distant reading" definition="Franco Moretti's method of analyzing literature computationally across thousands of texts to reveal patterns invisible to close reading of individual works" />" — analyzing literature not through close attention to individual texts but through computational aggregation of patterns across thousands — requires exactly this kind of structured, machine-readable output. The diagnostic model enables composability: an actantial analysis can be cross-referenced with a Proppian analysis to identify where Greimas's Subject maps onto Propp's Hero function, revealing structural homologies that close reading might miss.<Cite id={8} author="Jockers, Matthew L." title="Macroanalysis: Digital Methods and Literary History" source="University of Illinois Press" year={2013} /> Jockers's macroanalytic method depends on the ability to aggregate and compare structured outputs across corpora — the diagnostic format is designed to feed precisely this kind of computational literary scholarship.
      </p>
	</span>
</ShibuiContent>
