      <h2>Fountain Integration and Protocol Framework</h2>
      <p>
        The system includes native support for the Fountain screenplay format, enabling direct ingestion of professional scripts from Highland 2, Fade In, or VS Code without format conversion. The Fountain parser decomposes scripts into structured scene objects with character, dialogue, action, and transition metadata, which then feed into the diagnostic and framework analysis pipelines. This integration means that working screenwriters can run causal binding analysis or Proppian morphological decomposition against their actual production scripts rather than manually annotated text files.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Protocol Framework defines a seven-level skill progression (P1 through P7) for practitioners using the system, documented in <code>specs/08-protocol-framework/</code> with corresponding skill implementations in <code>specs/09-protocol-skills/</code>. Levels P1 and P2 establish foundational awareness of narrative structure and the compendium's vocabulary. P3 and P4 involve diagnostic application to real scripts — running causal binding checks, identifying reorderability issues, flagging unnecessary scenes. P5 and P6 require multi-framework synthesis and Script Doctor facilitation, where the practitioner composes analyses across multiple frameworks and interprets cross-framework correspondences. P7 represents autonomous framework extension — the ability to formalize new narrative theories as computational models with typed outputs, confidence scoring, and test suites that integrate into the existing compendium. The protocol framework transforms the system from a tool into a pedagogical infrastructure, encoding not just what narrative theory says but how to learn to apply it computationally.<Cite id={9} author="Murray, Janet H." title="Hamlet on the Holodeck: The Future of Narrative in Cyberspace" source="MIT Press" year={1997} /> Murray's vision of the computer as a medium for procedural storytelling requires exactly this kind of progressive mastery path — the protocol levels ensure that practitioners develop genuine analytical competence rather than treating the system as a black box that produces labels.
      </p>

      <h2>Build History and Test Infrastructure</h2>
      <p>
        The project was built across eight phases from an open-view Claude Desktop research project spanning fifty-two files and twenty-seven conversation threads. The entire build history is traceable through architecture decision records in the <code>docs/adr/</code> directory.
      </p>

